 Shadowrunners can be called on by anyone to do anything...for the right price.
 Teams of runners will execute runs for various political factions; the
 types of runs will include sabotage, theft, assassination, transportation,
 and proliferation.
 
\layout Paragraph

Due to the covert nature of their operations, the police do not provide
 a realiable source of protection against shadowrunner attacks.
 Henceforth, corporations usually employ their own shadowrunners to protect
 their valuable assets.
 This need has also given rise to security corporations that specialize
 in the protection of people, buildings, information networks, and technology.
 
\layout Paragraph

The shadowrunners, however, are not immune to police prosecution; they must
 keep a low profile to avoid having their crimes recorded.
 Even if they successfully complete runs, if they are spotted, corporations
 often share their data on runners with the police...and other personal enemies
 of the shadowrunners in question.
\layout Subsection

The Player
\layout Paragraph

In Metropolis, the player controls a group of shadowrunners.
 They start out relatively inexperienced.
 As the game progresses and the shadowrunners successfully complete missions,
 their skills will improve as well as their resources, which enables them
 to take on more challenging missions and purchase more sophisticated gear.
 
\layout Section

Setting
\layout Subsection

Hawaii
\layout Paragraph

The setting for Metropolis is a futuristic Hawaii.
 The city will feature sleek dome shaped cars with a 1950's spin.
 There are several design sketches available that demonstrate this style.
 The setting will also include underwater cities that are scattered around
 the islands; the islands are the hub of the surrounding cities.
 
